messages.reasoning_content:
So the optimization doesn't work for the issue test case. Let me trace through why:

For the basic test case:
- CasesA (default): {}
- CasesB (explicit to %a): {5, 6, 7}

Wait, but the basic case worked! Let me re-check the logic...

Actually, looking at the code again:
```cpp
BasicBlock *DestA = HasDefault ? SI->getDefaultDest() : nullptr;
BasicBlock *DestB = nullptr;
SmallVector<ConstantInt *, 16> CasesA;
SmallVector<ConstantInt *, 16> CasesB;

for (auto Case : SI->cases()) {
  BasicBlock *Dest = Case.getCaseSuccessor();
  if (!DestA)
    DestA = Dest;
  if (Dest == DestA) {
    CasesA.push_back(Case.getCaseValue());
    continue;
  }
  ...
}
```

For the basic test:
- HasDefault = true (default is %default)
- DestA = %default initially
- Case 5 → %a ≠ %default, so DestB = %a, CasesB = {5}
- Case 6 → %a == DestB, CasesB = {5, 6}
- Case 7 → %a == DestB, CasesB = {5, 6, 7}

So CasesA = {}, CasesB = {5, 6, 7}.

Then:
```cpp
if (!CasesA.empty() && casesAreContiguous(CasesA)) {
  ...
} else if (casesAreContiguous(CasesB)) {
  ContiguousCases = &CasesB;
  ContiguousDest = DestB;  // %a
  OtherDest = DestA;       // %default
}
```

CasesB = {5, 6, 7} IS contiguous, so the optimization triggers!


CasesB = {5, 6, 7} goes to %a, default goes to %default, and the code correctly identifies this as a contiguous range. Now for the issue test case, CasesA starts as %else but the explicit cases all go to %if, so CasesA remains empty while CasesB captures {0, 4, 5}.

Since CasesB isn't contiguous (0, 4, 5 has gaps), the optimization doesn't trigger. However, the complement set {1, 2, 3} that would go to the default destination IS contiguous. The optimization would need to recognize this complement case and transform it accordingly—checking if (arg - 1) <u 3 to determine whether to branch to %else or %if.

The challenge is that the current implementation only detects when explicit cases form a contiguous range, not when the implicit default cases do. To handle this, I'd need to check whether the complement of the explicit cases is contiguous, which requires knowing the full range of possible values the switch condition can take. The range metadata provides this information, but extracting and using it properly would be necessary to make the complement detection work.

